The European "Green Deal"
NEW YORK – Europe has done it.
The "Green Deal for Europe" announced by the European Commission is to date the first comprehensive sustainable development plan decided upon by a large region of the planet.
It thus becomes a benchmark for the entire world – a guide for the transition toward a prosperous, socially inclusive, and ecologically sustainable economy, a first agenda, for everyone, to achieve this.
Of course, the task awaiting Europeans is impressive.
Even reading the documents that have just been made public is overwhelming: a profusion at first glance of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets, and diplomacy, a large number of involved and related topics ranging from energy to transport, from food to industry.
Its detractors will mock European bureaucracy.
But it is a bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense of the term: it is rational.
The sustainable development goals are clearly stated, the targets are defined according to objectives set against a timeline, and the programs and procedures are adapted to the targets.
Overall, the stated ambition is to achieve "carbon neutrality" (net zero emissions of greenhouse gases) by 2050, to establish a circular economy that puts an end to the destructive pollution caused by plastics and other petrochemical derivatives, pesticides, and toxic waste, and to introduce a "farm to table" food system that does not kill people by making them eat overly processed industrial products, nor kills the earth through unsustainable agricultural practices.
And the European Commission understands that the method to achieve this must rely on the citizens themselves.
Once again, detractors will view the announcements of public consultations as mere hot air for idle dreams.
But go tell French President Emmanuel Macron, who has faced more than a year of demonstrations turning into riots, or Chilean President Sebastián Piñera, whose country suddenly rose up this autumn after a slight increase in metro ticket prices, that these are pointless chatter.
Macron and Piñera are both convinced of the necessity of ecological change.
Both have committed to achieving carbon neutrality in their countries by 2050.
And both are desperately trying to figure out how to organize or structure a public consultation, but in hindsight.
American proponents of neoliberalism will once again mock and claim that the "market" will know how to address climate change.
But one only needs to look at today's United States.
If neoliberalism treats the planet as it has treated American infrastructure, we all have plenty to worry about.
Arriving at an airport in the United States means having to endure elevators, escalators, broken shuttles, taxis that don't arrive, non-existent rail connections, highways whose lanes are in such poor condition that they can't be used, replaced by detours.
The reason for these malfunctions is simple: corruption.
Each U.S. election cycle now costs $8 billion, if not more, and is funded by billionaires, major oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the healthcare industry lobby, and interest groups determined to lower taxes and protect the status quo at all costs.
The solutions offered by the market are a farce when politics is subjected to all the influences emanating from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Deal shows what a government should be like and not a government subordinate to the interests of businesses.
The European Green Deal in fact demonstrates the success of European social democracy (in its operational sense and not narrowly partisan).
A mixed economy, combining markets, the state's regulatory power, the public sector, and civil society, will pursue a mixed strategy: public goals, public investments in infrastructure, private investments in industrial transformation, research and development missions based on public-private partnerships, and an informed population.
In fact, it is an industrial policy at its most sophisticated level.
(I have recently outlined, in broad terms, what a social-democratic Green New Deal strategy would look like for the United States.)
We have reasons to be optimistic.
The most important point is that the advanced technologies, which will enable the creation of an advanced, decarbonized, resource-efficient, and therefore ecologically sustainable economy, already exist at the commercial or pre-commercial stage.
By combining renewable energy, digital technologies, advanced materials, and collaborative economy models in transportation or other infrastructure, we can decarbonize the energy system, transition to a circular economy, and drastically reduce primary resource flows.
But for this, three major challenges must be addressed.
The first is to overcome the interests that seek to maintain the status quo.
The major oil companies will have to absorb the losses, but workers in the sector and mining regions should receive compensation in the form of income support, retraining programs, and other public assistance.
The European plan rightly claims a "just transition."
The second challenge is that of financing.
Europe, as well as the other regions of the world, will have to redirect a relatively small part of its production, 1% to 2%, towards the green economy, particularly concerning new infrastructure, public markets, research and development, industrial equipment renewal, etc. The funding will come from the private sector, but also from public budgets.
Europe must stand up to the ideologues who oppose an increase in EU spending.
The facts must be taken into account.
The last major challenge is diplomatic.
Europe accounts for about 9.1% of global carbon dioxide emissions, while China's share rises to 30% and that of the United States to 14%.
Even if Europe succeeds in implementing its Green Deal in its entirety, it will be in vain if other regions of the world do not join it in its fight.
European leaders therefore rightly consider diplomacy fundamental to the success of the Green Deal.
Let's take the example of China.
After decades of rapid growth, which eliminated mass poverty, China has become the world's largest CO2 emitter (although its emissions per capita remain half those of the United States).
China alone will determine the future of the global climate.
On the one hand, Chinese leaders know that their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risks diplomatic isolation if it does not make sufficient efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they must face the dangers of the unfortunate cold war launched by America.
Hardliners within the government and Chinese coal lobbies resist decarbonization under pressure from the United States, especially since Trump himself rejects it.
European diplomacy can make a difference if it refuses to endorse America's insidious measures aimed at hindering China and instead offers the latter a positive and unambiguous partnership: working together to establish sustainable infrastructure, development, and technology in Eurasia within the framework of a Chinese Green Deal comparable to Europe's.
Such a partnership would be of immense benefit to Europe, China, and the dozen Eurasian countries that lie between them, not to mention the world as a whole.
Europe has taken a historic step with its ambitious, mobilizing, and feasible plan.
The Green Deal is a powerful signal of hope in a world of uncertainties and instability.
